segments.text: Tracking Sir Donald Riggs, E. Riggs.
What's your title now?
I'm the Dean of the University Library.
Uh-huh.
And you've had a couple of things that you've done here, right?
Are you moving to another position, I guess?
I'm going over to the School of Information in January.
I've been here six years.
This is the first job, except for one, and I've stayed more than five years.
Really?
Yeah.
At Arizona State where we built five new libraries and added 112 new positions, I stayed 11 and a half years.
But could you tell me a little bit about what the new duties will involve?
Well, I will be teaching courses in library leadership and academic libraries and advanced management.
How do you feel about, I mean, it is kind of a, of course Michigan is
considered one of the innovators, right?
This digital library and stuff.
How do you feel about that?
Let's just start over the very general entry.
Well, we have the, this library has one of the better collections in many areas.
Collections of what?
Well, for example, research collections.
We have the best mathematics collection.
We have the best dentistry, academic dentistry library collection.
We have one of the better
Faulkner collections.
And we have, right Toby?
Our Japanese collection is about the second best.
So when I came here, one of the things I wanted to do was create an environment whereby we could take a leadership role in digitizing library materials and also work with corporations.
And for example, we're working with the Mellon Foundation.
We're digitizing ten
social science, well, 10 history and economics journals from 1990 all the way back.
And Bill Bowen, who used to be the president of the Princeton University, and has taken a very keen interest in this area.
So, we're doing that work here at Michigan.
Right.
And, um, we're going.
Go ahead.
We're working with, on this sheet, with the Cornell University and digitizing about 5,000
volumes of classics between 1850 and 1950, those items which are no longer protected by copyright.
Right.
So I was telling you, Kobe, copyright is the key.
Exactly.
Kobe said, why are they picking such and such a date?
I said, I don't know, but my sense is,
There's no copyright problem there.
That's right.
No, I was out at Cornell two weeks ago, so two days there.
So you sold it, probably, at some of it.
I sold a lot of it.
I've been to Stanford and the Waterloo Congress.
I've been to Corvus out in Washington State, so I'm, you know, I'm not... And, of course, everywhere you go, you hear Michigan, and you talk about digitizing books.
Now, at Cornell,
For instance, some of the things they digitize, they then deaccession and get rid of.
What do you people do with things that you digitize?
We haven't gotten rid of anything yet.
Those ten journals which we're sending down to Barbados, actually, to have a digit scan because of the labor.
However, the Mellon Foundation is paying more than the prevailing wage, and Bill Bowen has been challenged on it.
Are you exploiting people in Barbados?
Are they kidding?
I'm sorry.
No, they're not.
No, they're not children.
They're working as equipment.
Right.
So, we have to tear those journals apart, and here's something.
For example, we may only have one copy of the journal, but a place like Harvard may have ten copies of that same title, full background.
So, when we bring it back, we re-bind it.
You do.
Yeah, we do.
At Cornell, when they break them up, I mean, they're going off to
parks unknown, probably the landfill.
I mean, you're aware of that.
Yeah.
What do you think?
Should we keep both?
I think publishers are going to... I don't have a position on this, by the way.
I'm just really interested in, you know, what your attitude is on this.
I think for a while we will probably keep the paper copy as well, Steve.
But eventually we're going to, for example, for our card catalog,
You know, many universities just threw them out, and that person wrote the article for the New Yorker.
Nicholson Baker.
Thank you.
Yeah, I couldn't think of his name.
But when I came, I told my—we had not filed any cards.
I came here in 1991.
We had not filed any cards in the card catalog since 1989 or so.
And I told my faculty group, I'm going to move that card catalog out so we can develop this Knowledge Navigation Center.
And they said, well, give us a couple more years, and so on and so forth.
We moved it down in the basement, took it out of that primary real estate, and we still have our card catalog.
Not one peep out of the faculty here.
That's what they were saying.
They said, some faculty member said, you know, all of my material, most of my material is reflected in the card catalog, and it's not new material, so it won't be online.
I said, well, it will be, but they said, well, we can still access it better, and so on and so forth.
Will we keep the card catalog forever?
I don't think so, Toby.
Well, that happens.
As long as I'm alive.
Well, you have to.
Thanks very much.
As long as I'm alive.
Now, there's a brand new one.
Do you want to call him?
Do you want me to call him now?
Could you?
Maybe you could do that, but then I could, yeah.
And just tell him, I'm asking Stephen to come up here while Toby's here, and we've got this Brodsky collection.
Just here, a little while ago, the story on the Robert Brodsky.
This guy was?
Yeah.
He's missing.
Well,
I'll give him a call.
Okay.
How long are you going to be here, Toby?
Until I leave.
Toby will be back on Monday the 2nd of December.
One of the reasons we are making things happen here as compared with some other universities is the fact that I discovered we couldn't go on this alone.
We don't have the expertise in the library.
So when Elsevier came out with their TULIP project, that's where they took material science journals and put it online.
There were nine universities, I think, involved.
We were able to get the project done faster than the other ones because we engage other people on campus, like our School of Engineering.
And I have one person we lost to the University of Virginia, John Price Wilkins, who is probably the best in the country in the Humanities Tax Initiative.
Anyway, John went down to Charlottesville.
He didn't like it there, and Yale offered him a job, and so I wanted him back here.
I didn't want him to leave in the first place.

Anyway, so I called the dean of the arts and sciences, the director of University Press, and the dean of the library school, and I asked each other, can you give me fifteen thousand dollars to pay toward John's salary?
They'd like if the library didn't come up that much.
And they all said, we'd be happy to do this.
So we're using other people's mothers in a sense.

And this person who you met here a few minutes ago, Wendy Roger, she's employed as our Assistant Director for Digital Library Initiatives, which she's employed, her salary's paid 40% by library, 40% by information technology, and 20% by the School of Information.
So we're using a kind of a, I suppose, a collaborative effort here on campus.
And that's how we're making some of these things happen,
University libraries really don't, on their existing staffs, do not have the expertise.
We need to make these things move.
Now, Cornell was, I couldn't believe how set up they are.
Yeah.

Now, the assistant librarian there, I can't think of his name right now, not Sarah, but the man just immediately beneath her, he said that they have been mandated by their trustees to limit, as of the year 2000, five million books.
Have you heard that?
And that's it.
No more on a campus.
Outrage.
Burn the books.
Undoubtedly, there is pressure.
What are we going to do with all this stuff?
We've got this great technology.
We can scan it.
Who needs the printed book?
It was interesting.
My provost told me, I said, we have 1.6 million volumes in storage, which we can get within 24 hours.
Where do you keep them?
about a mile from here.
What do you call that facility?
Is it just part of the library?
It's called the BUHR, B-U-H-R, that's the name of the building.
BUHR.
I've been to the Harvard Depository, which is about 20 miles out of Cambridge.
Yeah, but this is just down the road, down in Green Street.
Well, we have 1.6 million volumes there, and the provost asked me, when I told him, I said, Bernie, we need more.
We have to expand that area, because
It's my understanding, we have one of the largest acquisitions budgets here.
But since I've been here, I've really pushed that because we also buy our non-print materials out of that, the multimedia resources.
So last year, the University of Michigan got the largest increase of any major research university library in the United States and Canada.
Is that right?
I can show you this.
What's the number?
How much money did you have to spend on acquisitions?
Last year we had...
about $11 million.
This year we'll be going over $12 million.
Really?
Yeah.
That's for the whole university.
Also, last year—I can show you statistics, though—that last year the University of Michigan Library spent more for journals than any other university, including Harvard and Yale and all those.
This university, since I've been here, when I came our budget was $19 million.
Now it's $27 million.
So we've added—and a lot of that's in the accuracy.
I've heard a lot of them resign this year.
And we've got an 8-point this past year.
Well, when we got the 9.1%, the average was something like 3% among research libraries.
And, of course, how do you break that down in terms of, you say, the multimedia stuff has kind of folded into that.
What percentage goes to multimedia?
Yeah, we're up to about, we're up to about, this doesn't sound much, but it's much when you compare federal libraries, about 7% now.
Seven.
Seven percent.
Seven percent of that figure is for...
Non-print.
Non-print things?
Well, I would have expected it to be more than that.
Really?
Yeah, but see, there's no university library is spending, say, ten percent.
Yeah.
And most, I was in a conference... So yours is less, actually.
The lower percentage than most... No, ours is more.
Really?
Yeah.
It's closer to four, four percent.
And some people are not buying any
CD-ROMs and, you know, database, electronic databases out of their budget, out of their materials.
They try to get supplemental funding, but it's only like one time.
We're trying to build it into our base, and administration has it.
Part of the whole project.
We have this one project, this Humanities Tech Initiative.
Let me tell you just how the machine has helped scholarship.
We use a software engine called Pat Lecter.
P-A-T-L-E-C-L-E-C-T-O-R.
It's a hyphenated word?
Yeah, out of the University of Waterloo.
And a professor was showing this one day.
And he was saying, he used four words.
He said, you know, I'm looking to see how many times these four words are connected or strung together.
And the four words are like, in the search of.
Rather simple.
So he sits there, and there are 3,000 old English texts.
because the machinist did it.
Another part would say, so what, you know?
But I said, is this really important?
But see, that's information, what we talked about again.
That's concordance.
Yeah, and here's what he... Well, you link concordance.
Yeah.
It's one word, right?
Mm-hmm, yeah.
But see, what he was saying, he was saying, for people who study linguistics, that's important, to have those words, I mean, you know.
And I said, but how many... I said, just roughly, what would have taken you, you know, to do it manually?
He said, 17 years.
And if you think about that, that's quite an impact on scholarship.
I don't want to belittle the importance of that, but it's kind of... Well, no, but when we talk about the information age, this is information.
Yes.
Not knowledge.
It's not knowledge.
Right.
It's data.
It's information.
And it's extraordinarily useful.
And I'd be a fool and a hypocrite and say I don't use it myself every day of the year because I do.
That's right.
When I'm asking you for your website, I say I'll do this at home.
Oh, yes.
Why waste valuable time here?
Except you won't be able to do it.
I think you will.
I can do it.
Pretty good.
You might be shocked to learn, Toby.
You're a great computer literate.
You have to be.
Oh, yeah.
You have to be today.
See, this is where the students know more.
At one time, professors could stand up before their students and display their knowledge and all the great classics and, you know, all the great books and all the erotic articles.
Now, these students—the professor said, the students know more than I do, what's on the web.
Isn't that interesting?
Well, I know that.
So, this is where the librarians are going to have to work hard and work with the faculty to get them up to speed, so to speak.
This is, you know, a softball pitch, but what is a librarian's function historically and today, in your view?
It's called information now.
Did you notice the School of Libraries is now called School of Information?
The role of the librarian has been, it's been a multi-role, identifying and ordering, organizing, articulating collections.
Now, the role of the librarian, it still involves that.

librarian serves as a navigator, someone, the navigator for online resources, someone who can, who can identify and seek out and locate and customize information online, you know, for the, for the user.
Before digital, before the digital environment, we would have bibliographic resources.
You can get the author and title.
Now, you can bring that information right to the user's workstation.
And see, I go, I go throughout the country and get speeches on
on universal access to materials and— Is this a specialty of yours?
Mm-hmm.
National—I was just in—I missed Toby's conference.
I was in Prague.
I gave two speeches over there.
One was on human values and the—and cyberspace.
You got a copy of that?
I don't think I have one here, but I can see you.
Would you?
Yeah.
And my other— I'll just have to—I left my cards in my briefcase.
And my other—my other talk was on—
universal access, a digital library, let's not forget the have-nots.
Do you know two, one half of the world's population lives two miles from near his telephone?
Think of it.
One half of the world's population lives two miles from near his telephone.
Think of this.
25% of the public school children who are attending
public schools in the city of Chicago come from homes without telephones.
Now, talking about haves and have-nots, but it's not just a money issue.
In some countries, for example... How many of them are going to have computers, then?
Well, yeah, if they don't have... Maybe the book is more suited for people who are the have-nots.
Maybe this technology does exclude a major... Well, I think, as a matter of fact, it might be one of the most serious problems in our
Civilization, in the future, if you think about my, you know, because the people have access to all this information, it's going to be much farther ahead, I think, and those two do not.
And, but there are other, it's just, I mean, sure, money's one issue, but there are many other issues, too.
In some countries, they don't want you to have access to information.
I mean, they control what you, what they want you to read.
No, you used to be a crime to teach black people how to read.
Exactly.
Yeah, we haven't gone much farther.
Yeah.
I'm sorry, I was off on my track.
That's okay.
How about, you mentioned you have this very aggressive acquisitions program.
How about deaccessions?
You know, and also the librarian, you more or less characterized him or her as a person who marshals and gathers and organizes them.
How about, you know, you have 1.2 million books stored a mile off campus.
Clearly the books you've put out there are books that nobody's using.
Those are books that no one's checked out, say, in the last 10 years.
So you're making a decision there.
We want to keep them.
We don't want to deaccession them.
But then what's the step after that?
Do you decide that there are any collections that haven't been used in 20 or 30 years, that there's nobody teaching, and that maybe we could use that space for something else?
Yeah, we discard.
We have books there.
Yeah, but how about deaccessioning collections?
Do you do that?
You do that?
Yeah.
Can you think of any collections?
Well, we've taken some collections that we have.
We think that should be, that would be better.
Okay.
Thank you very much.
Yeah, this is it.
Sidebars.
You don't tell the donor's family, don't you?
I don't think he's talking about special collection.
No, I'm not talking about a rare collection.
Did you use the word collection?
I did, yeah.
For example, we had some, I think there were some dissertations in Southeast Asia stored out by, what's this airport out here?
I can't think of the name.
Willow Run.
Yeah, Willow Run.
When I heard about it, I said, we don't have access to this.
Let's send those down to the Center for Research Libraries down in, it's a storage facility.
which they specialize in things like that down in Chicago, and they were so happy to get that, because they handle foreign dissertations, and I knew that, so that's an example.

Let me tell you, I didn't finish one story I was going to tell you, and that's when my provost said, why don't we, rather than sending all those building this physical storage facility onto the bureaus to handle these books, why don't we just digitize them?
So we did a real quick cost analysis.
You did.
So you actually looked into this.
We did.
What if we were to take a 300-page book?
How much would it cost to digitize it?
And we came out with something like a cost of about $75.
But those costs are always going down, too.
Well, no.
As a matter of fact, we've discovered that was a conservative cost.
That was based on scanning.
Like $5 a page, something like that?
Yeah.
Well, they said $0.40 a page, I think.
That's not bad.
Cornell's got it down to $0.18 a page now.
But see, the...
The Mellon Foundation is finding out it's costing more than they'd expected, so I don't know what Cornell's getting its figures.
So what are they calling building a better point?
Mm-hmm.
And see, Bill Bowen is the—he's the economist of, you know, he was president of Princeton.
He comes out—this adjacent project, he takes a special interest in.
Anyway, for the same cost, it would cost, you know, for—if we were to digitize 50,000 volumes, we could build
a storage facility that would accommodate a million volumes.
So they'd probably say, well, economics doesn't add up, so forget about digitizing.
But see, but then again... But what if the numbers were right, though?
I wouldn't have any difficulty in digitizing if they're no longer protected.
Now, people like Toby and the faculty would probably be after me, but no.
I mean, if they're not used,
And when that cost comes down to that point, then... But see, you can ask... It's numbers.
What you're telling me is it's the economics.
The only thing standing between you and getting rid of 50,000 books is how much it's going to cost.
If the price was right, you'd say it's okay.
Oh, I think so.
And how would you pick the 50,000 books?
Which 50,000 books would you pick out of your six million?
Well, okay.
For example, in the storage facility, naturally you have to pick the ones that are no longer protected by copyright.
I would probably pick the ones that have not circulated.
I would be real safe to say in the last 15 years.
And when you say not circulated, you mean so much as one person checking it out.
Right, right.
Can you differentiate between use and circulation?
No.
Yeah, I can.
I do.
I can, you know, in my own life.
Well, these are books that haven't seen the storage facility.
This is an academic library, so we can't measure them.
See, in the storage facility, it's closed stacks.
See, so we know who, actually, the book has moved out the shelf because the faculty do not go into the stack area.
It's a closed stack in the storage facility.
You use the words concurrently, use them without separation, use and circulate.
That's my question.
Hello?
Well, I left my card on the card.
It used to be that the library got money based upon the circulation tables.
And we started yelling and screaming about that.
Yeah, no, we don't do that.
I use use as my word, not circulate.
You use the two words interchangeably.
That's all the manscaped.
Only in the beer facility, Toby.
Because, see, there, here we have open stacks.
So we have a lot of people go into the stack area.
And they'll take books off the shelf and sit down at the table and read them right there.
That's what I call use.
Yeah, right, right.
But see, in the beer facility, if they want a book, it has to be retrieved, okay?
So we know, we keep a record, that book was actually called for.
It may be only used in the library there at the beer facility, and it's not checked out.
I'm following all that.
Don't y'all tell me that I'm giving you my email address.
Well, you may have several questions after you.
It's bouncing from circulation to use, and for me, use is a higher form.
Yeah, that's fax, email, phone, address.
Okay, good.
That's more than information I have on my card.
But let's go back.
You said you'd do a... Would you want to... We didn't want him finish what he was saying.
No.
This is interesting.
You don't want to finish?
Yeah, you read all that stuff.
Okay.
We said you'd have a group, maybe.
Maybe you'd have somebody study the books, copyright, and then we stopped.
So let's go.
We're on.
Great.
Thank you.
Thanks very much.
Okay.
Thank you.
Wonderful.
Thank you.
All right.
Okay, I'll go back and talk about how I would determine.
What I wrote is just to be in the safe side.
Yeah, I would consult with the faculty and tell them what I plan to do.

These books have not been used in 15 years, therefore I want to digitize them and save space and also make them accessible to the world, so to speak, which they cannot, they're not accessible if they had to come here.
And then what would you do with the 50,000 books?
I would sell them, yeah.
I would put them in book sales.
So there's no particular... Or give them to another... There's no attachment, then, that you don't feel any special attachment, then, to the printed book.
I mean, I think... No, but that's going a little bit too far.
I'm a strong believer in collections, in special collections.
And I also, there's just something about a book.
You know, and the computer won't do this for some time, but even the olio from the smell of it.
I mean, that turns me on.
Maybe that turns you off the doctor.
No.
It turns me on a very, very way.
No, but when I go on.
Especially his own books.
Right.
When I go into special collections, and see what my projections are, and I've done some writing on this, about that we're going to have a demise of the reference book as we know it.
You know, like book books.
Who's who in America?
And his books, you know, they're going to be.
And I think that's correct, by the way.
Mm-hmm.
Mike Keller at Stanford, you know, points out, he said, you get some monographs that cost, you're only going to sell three or four hundred of them at best.
They're going to cost you two, three hundred dollars to buy.
And in the sciences, they're going to be obsolete the day they come out.
Doesn't it make better sense to make them available here?
Go to what you want, download print that you want.
The graphics of the color now are such that they're extraordinary.
It's awfully hard.
To argue with that, it's awfully hard to argue with putting the OED online.
I know.
In the words of Christophageism, the Encyclopedia Britannica.
You know, I mean, you have to acknowledge there are certain areas that it makes sense.
That's right.
Well, whatever.
You know, you can't be a total Luddite here in some of this stuff.
I'd like to see all the reference books.
I would like to see journals.
I think someday we will see the demise of the journals we know of.
I think you'll go in and you'll access information on the topic.
and you have proceedings, book chapters, and so-called journals.
My concern, I think the publishers are very concerned about are they going to lose their shirts with some of the journals, because these journals are really expensive.
You know, there's almost a racket going on here whereby professors generate all this intellectual property, and then for some journals now you have to pay $200
per page in order to have your article.
So if you have a 20-page article, what is that?
What's that, $4,000?
You send the $4,000 into the public in order to get promoted and to get tenure.
That's right.
It's almost blackmail, isn't it?
Oh, yeah.
Then they send this.
That counts as a publication?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Journal.
Journal.
Yeah, journal.
See, a journal article.
That's where most of the faculty, that's how they... It's close to a book.
It's a journal.
It's beneath a book.
For example, to... The closest thing to a book.
I added this journal.
I added this journal.
This is the best journal in academic library, academic research life.
Yeah.
I'm the editor of that particular journal.
Now, our rejection rate is, we reject 65% of the articles that are submitted.
Now, that's a high rejection rate.
In other words, only 35% of the articles.
Can I have a copy?
Yeah, you can have a copy.
Matt, thank you.
I'm one of these people who wants everything, by the way.
Okay.
My editorial here is working with the faculty, and that pretty much articulates what I said earlier.
At one time, faculty members knew all the literature.
Now the students know what they do on the web.
But back to this story, then the publishers sell all of this property that's created by the faculty back to the universities at an enormous price.
Some journals like
The Journal of Physics is like 20,000 a year.
These are enormous prices.
How much longer can universities continue to pay all of this, you know?
So... They're supposed to share.
Well, we are sharing.
I'd like to talk a little bit about that.
Why don't you talk a little bit about that?
Okay, I know we're jumping all over the place here.
That's fine.
I like jumping.
Anyway, when I came here in 1991, I went to my provost, Gil Whittaker, and I said, the Big Ten Universities need to do something.
library-wise.
I said, we need to develop more interdependence among these, now there are 13 libraries.
Penn State is part of the Big Ten.
So, actually, it became an athletic conference, going into the library.
Right.
It's called the Committee on Institutional Cooperation, CIC.
And I mentioned to Gil, I said, we need to do something, we need to do something fast.
And he said, well, why don't you develop a strategic plan?
Which I did, and I went and made a presentation as a provost.
And they liked it.
Naturally, but to see, they can oversimplify and think they're going to save a lot of money.
We have saved some money, and I can give you some documentation on that.
Okay.
Yeah.
One of the things, for example, we are taking the Modern Language Association Bibliography here.
I'm talking about the online database.
We're sharing the other 12.
The site license.
But we're saving money.
I mean, all of us are saving money.
The University of Wisconsin is working with Baustein.
That's... Oh, Treonis.
Could you come in here for a second?
I'm trying those guys.
This guy knows exactly what he's doing.
This is our Greek papyrologist.
And Nick was interested in seeing this.
Maybe you could give a demonstration briefly or sometime.
He could pull it up maybe on his homepage.
Can he pull it up?
Maybe there's no need to.
You can have a Luke.
We have a lot of stuff at this month.
It's not appearing yet.
It will appear sometime at the beginning of December.
Okay.
But there is quite a bit online already.
That I can do it.
From samples to exhibits online.
Okay.
That I can do it.
Good.
I'm glad you came down.
Well, June actually has left a message on the machine.
Well, it's probably... We've got to copy the article for it.
You know, I have given away at least 120 copies.
And I kept...
Now, aren't you glad you did it?
Yes, yes, yes.
One of the pieces, the dean said, you better write something.
And then it appeared for a while.
And then she said, you better rewrite.
I rewrote, eventually came out last year.
Working with editors, I know.
The people keep saying that the experience alone that comes out of this article is very useful for similar projects.
This is the oldest collection we have, and it reflects how
This enabling technology can improve the human condition.
I think that when you read this, you'll have a much better appreciation of our civilization.
But I, yeah, but I think the technology... Of course, when you take all your thoughts in your face.
Well, I think it's going to help, you know, with the health and these developing countries.
It's going to help in so many ways.
And with libraries, it's just one way.
Of course, when you have a scholar that comes in and wants to look at these papyrus,
